SENATE BILL 807
A1 6lr3130
CF HB 1590
By: Senator Bailey
Introduced and read first time: February 6, 2026
Assigned to: Finance
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
Senate action: Adopted with floor amendments
Read second time: March 5, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Alcoholic Beverages – Class 8 Farm Brewery and Class 10 Farm Distillery
3 Licenses
4 FOR the purpose of establishing a Class 10 farm distillery license that authorizes a license
5 holder to distill, rectify, bottle, and sell at wholesale or retail distilled spirits
6 produced on the licensed farm; requiring that a holder of a Class 8 farm brewery
7 license or a Class 10 farm distillery license engage in certain agritourism activity;
8 altering certain standards and requirements for food service under a Class 8 farm
9 brewery license; providing an exception to a prohibition against issuing an alcoholic
10 beverages license for a premises that does not comply with local zoning laws for
11 certain Class 8 farm brewery licenses and Class 10 farm distillery licenses;
12 authorizing the holder of a Class 10 farm distillery license to apply for and obtain
13 additional Class 10 farm distillery licenses under certain circumstances and a Class
14 8 liquor wholesaler’s license; and generally relating to Class 8 farm brewery and
15 Class 10 farm distillery alcoholic beverages licenses.
16 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
17 Article – Alcoholic Beverages and Cannabis
18 Section 1–405, 2–210, and 2–212
19 Annotated Code of Maryland
20 (2024 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
21 BY adding to
22 Article – Alcoholic Beverages and Cannabis
23 Section 2–203.1
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0807*

2 SENATE BILL 807
1 Annotated Code of Maryland
2 (2024 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
3 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
4 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
5 Article – Alcoholic Beverages and Cannabis
6 1–405.
7 (a) A license may not be issued for a premises unless the premises conforms to all
8 requirements set out in this article or the Tax – General Article.
9 (b) (1) [A] EXCEPT FOR THIS SUBSECTION DOES NOT APPLY TO A CLASS
10 8 FARM BREWERY LICENSE ISSUED UNDER § 2–210 OF THIS ARTICLE OR A CLASS 10
11 FARM DISTILLERY LICENSE ISSUED UNDER § 2–203.1 OF THIS ARTICLE, A IF THE
12 HOLDER OF THE CLASS 8 FARM BREWERY LICENSE HOLDS A CLASS 8 FARM
13 BREWERY LICENSE FIRST ISSUED ON OR BEFORE JULY 1, 2015.
14 (2) A license or an alcoholic beverages permit may not be issued for a
15 premises unless the premises conforms with all zoning laws, regulations, or ordinances
16 passed in accordance with Division I of the Land Use Article.
17 2–203.1.
18 (A) THERE IS A CLASS 10 FARM DISTILLERY LICENSE.
19 (B) THE LICENSE MAY BE ISSUED ONLY TO A HOLDER OF A CLASS 8 FARM
20 BREWERY LICENSE.
21 (C) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, A LICENSE
22 HOLDER MAY SELL AND DELIVER SPIRITS PRODUCED ON THE LICENSED FARM TO:
23 (I) A WHOLESALER LICENSED TO SELL AND DELIVER SPIRITS IN
24 THE STATE; OR
25 (II) A PERSON IN ANOTHER STATE AUTHORIZED TO ACQUIRE
26 SPIRITS.
27 (2) THE DISTILLED SPIRITS TO BE SOLD AND DELIVERED UNDER
28 PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION SHALL BE MANUFACTURED WITH AN
29 INGREDIENT FROM A MARYLAND AGRICULTURAL PRODUCT, INCLUDING CORN,
30 GRAIN, AND FRUIT, PRODUCED ON THE LICENSED FARM.
31 (3) THE LICENSED FARM SHALL BE:

SENATE BILL 807 3
1 (I) AN AGRIBUSINESS ENGAGED IN THE PRODUCTION,
2 SHOWCASING, PREPARATION, AND SALE OF FARM PRODUCTS; AND
3 (II) ACTIVELY ENGAGED IN AGRITOURISM BY EXPOSING THE
4 PUBLIC TO FARMING AND VALUE–ADDED FARMING PRACTICES.
5 (D) A LICENSE HOLDER MAY:
6 (1) (I) SUBJECT TO ITEM (II) OF THIS ITEM, ESTABLISH AND
7 OPERATE A PLANT ON THE LICENSED FARM FOR DISTILLING, RECTIFYING, AND
8 BOTTLING BRANDY, RUM, WHISKEY, ALCOHOL, AND NEUTRAL SPIRITS;
9 (II) HAVE MORE THAN ONE LICENSE ISSUED BY THE
10 COMMISSION AT THE SAME LOCATION IF THE LICENSE HOLDER:
11 1. MAINTAINS A SINGLE BRAND AT ANY TIME FOR EACH
12 PRODUCT OF BRANDY, RUM, WHISKEY, ALCOHOL, AND NEUTRAL SPIRIT THAT IS
13 DISTILLED, RECTIFIED, AND SOLD; AND
14 2. DOES NOT MANUFACTURE OR RECTIFY A PRODUCT OF
15 ANY OTHER BRAND FOR A SEPARATE ENTITY;
16 (III) HOLD OR OBTAIN:
17 1. A CLASS 7 LIMITED BEER WHOLESALER’S LICENSE;
18 OR
19 2. A CLASS 8 LIQUOR WHOLESALER’S LICENSE;
20 (2) ACQUIRE BULK ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES FROM THE HOLDER OF A
21 DISTILLERY OR RECTIFYING LICENSE IN THE STATE OR THE HOLDER OF A
22 NONRESIDENT DEALER’S PERMIT;
23 (3) AFTER ACQUIRING AN INDIVIDUAL STORAGE PERMIT UNDER §
24 2–113 OF THIS TITLE, STORE PRODUCTS MANUFACTURED ON THE LICENSED FARM;
25 (4) SELL AND DELIVER THE PRODUCTS MANUFACTURED UNDER THE
26 LICENSE FOR ON–PREMISES AND OFF–PREMISES CONSUMPTION;
27 (5) CONDUCT GUIDED TOURS OF THE PORTION OF THE LICENSED
28 FARM USED FOR DISTILLING, RECTIFYING, AND BOTTLING;

4 SENATE BILL 807
1 (6) SERVE PRODUCTS THAT ARE MANUFACTURED ON THE LICENSED
2 FARM OR BY ANOTHER MANUFACTURER IN THE STATE TO A CONSUMER AT NO
3 CHARGE OR FOR A FEE;
4 (7) SELL OR SERVE FOOD IF THE LICENSE HOLDER:
5 (I) IS LICENSED TO OPERATE A FOOD ESTABLISHMENT UNDER
6 TITLE 21, SUBTITLE 3 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE;
7 (II) USES A LICENSED FOOD TRUCK;
8 (III) USES A LICENSED CATERER; OR
9 (IV) IS SELLING OR SERVING COTTAGE INDUSTRY FOOD
10 PREPARED ON THE FARM UNDER § 21–330.1 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE;
11 AND
12 (8) IN ACCORDANCE WITH PARAGRAPH (C)(3) OF THIS SECTION:
13 (I) HOST FESTIVALS;
14 (II) PROVIDE LIVE MUSIC OR OTHER ENTERTAINMENT; OR
15 (III) RENT PORTIONS OF THE LICENSED FARM TO THE PUBLIC OR
16 PRIVATE INDIVIDUALS OR GROUPS FOR FUNCTIONS OR EVENTS, INCLUDING:
17 1. BANQUETS;
18 2. WEDDINGS;
19 3. ANNIVERSARY PARTIES;
20 4. BIRTHDAY PARTIES;
21 5. FUNDRAISERS; AND
22 6. OTHER SIMILAR CELEBRATIONS OR EVENTS.
23 (E) A LICENSE HOLDER MAY NOT:
24 (1) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN PARAGRAPH (D)(1) OF THIS SECTION:
25 (I) HOLD OR OBTAIN A WHOLESALER’S LICENSE; OR

SENATE BILL 807 5
1 (II) OWN, OPERATE, OR BE AFFILIATED IN ANY MANNER WITH
2 ANOTHER MANUFACTURER; OR
3 (2) DISTILL, RECTIFY, BOTTLE, OR SELL MORE THAN 100,000
4 GALLONS OF BRANDY, RUM, WHISKEY, ALCOHOL, OR NEUTRAL SPIRITS EACH
5 CALENDAR YEAR.
6 (F) A CLASS 10 FARM DISTILLERY MAY BE LOCATED ONLY AT THE PLACE
7 DESCRIBED IN THE LICENSE.
8 (G) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION AND
9 NOTWITHSTANDING ANY LOCAL LAW, A LICENSE HOLDER MAY EXERCISE THE
10 PRIVILEGES OF A CLASS 10 FARM DISTILLERY LICENSE.
11 (2) THE COMMISSION HAS EXCLUSIVE REGULATORY AUTHORITY
12 OVER THE OPERATION OF A CLASS 10 FARM DISTILLERY.
13 (H) THE ANNUAL LICENSE FEE:
14 (1) SHALL BE DETERMINED BY THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR; AND
15 (2) MAY NOT EXCEED $500.
16 2–210.
17 (a) There is a Class 8 farm brewery license.
18 (b) (1) Subject to paragraph (2) of this subsection, a license holder may sell
19 and deliver beer manufactured in a facility on the licensed farm or in a facility other than
20 one on the licensed farm to:
21 (i) a wholesaler licensed to sell and deliver beer in the State; or
22 (ii) a person in another state authorized to acquire beer.
23 (2) The beer to be sold and delivered under paragraph (1) of this subsection
24 shall be manufactured with an ingredient from a Maryland agricultural product, including
25 hops, grain, and fruit, produced on the licensed farm.
26 (3) THE LICENSED FARM SHALL BE:
27 (I) AN AGRIBUSINESS ENGAGED IN THE PRODUCTION,
28 SHOWCASING, PREPARATION, AND SALE OF FARM PRODUCTS; AND

6 SENATE BILL 807
1 (II) ACTIVELY ENGAGED IN AGRITOURISM BY EXPOSING THE
2 PUBLIC TO FARMING AND VALUE–ADDED FARMING PRACTICES.
3 (c) A license holder may:
4 (1) (i) sell beer produced by the license holder OR ANOTHER
5 MANUFACTURER IN THE STATE for on–premises and off–premises consumption;
6 (ii) in an amount not exceeding 6 fluid ounces per brand, provide
7 samples of beer that the license holder produces to a consumer:
8 1. at no charge; or
9 2. for a fee; AND
10 (iii) sell or serve[:
11 1. bread and other baked goods;
12 2. chili;
13 3. chocolate;
14 4. crackers;
15 5. cured meat;
16 6. fruits (whole and cut);
17 7. hard and soft cheese (whole and cut);
18 8. salads and vegetables (whole and cut);
19 9. ice cream;
20 10. jam;
21 11. jelly;
22 12. vinegar;
23 13. pizza;
24 14. prepackaged sandwiches and other prepackaged foods
25 ready to be eaten;

SENATE BILL 807 7
1 15. soup; and
2 16. condiments; and
3 (iv) subject to subsection (e)(2) of this section, sell or serve any] food
4 if the license holder:
5 1. is licensed to operate a food establishment under Title 21,
6 Subtitle 3 of the Health – General Article;
7 2. USES A LICENSED FOOD TRUCK;
8 3. USES A LICENSED CATERER; OR
9 4. IS SELLING OR SERVING COTTAGE INDUSTRY FOOD
10 PREPARED ON THE FARM UNDER § 21–330.1 OF THE HEALTH – GENERAL ARTICLE;
11 (2) store, in a segregated area approved by the Executive Director, beer
12 produced by the license holder for sale and delivery to a wholesaler licensed in the State or
13 a person outside the State authorized to acquire the beer;
14 (3) brew, bottle, or contract for not more than 15,000 barrels of beer each
15 calendar year;
16 (4) contract with the holder of a Class 2 rectifying license, a Class 5
17 brewery license, or a Class 7 micro–brewery license to brew and bottle beer from
18 ingredients produced on the licensed farm;
19 (5) import, export, and transport its beer in accordance with this section;
20 (6) store, brew, and bottle beer in a facility listed on a permit issued to the
21 license holder in accordance with § 2–113 of this title, for sale and delivery to a wholesaler
22 licensed in the State or a person outside the State authorized to acquire the beer, or
23 shipment back to the licensed farm, if:
24 (i) the license holder does not serve or sell beer at the warehouse;
25 and
26 (ii) the Executive Director has full access at all times to the
27 warehouse to enforce this article; [and]
28 (7) enter into a temporary delivery agreement with a distributor only for
29 delivery of beer to a beer festival or a wine and beer festival, and the return of any unused
30 beer, if:

