1 (3) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN A LOCAL FIRE SAFETY CODE, THE
2 COMMISSION MAY NOT LIMIT THE NUMBER OF VISITORS ON THE LICENSED
3 PREMISES.
4 (f) (1) This subsection does not apply to a permit issued under § 2–140 of this
5 title.
6 (2) A license holder at the location listed on the license may exercise the
7 RETAIL privileges of the license each day from 10 a.m. to 10 p.m.
8 (g) Except as provided in Division II of this article, a Class 8 farm brewery license
9 allows the license holder to operate 7 days a week.
10 (h) Nothing in this section limits the application of relevant provisions of Title 21
11 of the Health – General Article, and regulations adopted under that title, to a license holder.
12 (i) (1) A license holder may sponsor a multibrewery activity at the location
13 issued on the license that:
14 (i) includes the products of other Maryland breweries; and
15 (ii) provides for the sale of products in the manner authorized under
16 the license.
17 (2) In a segregated area approved by the Executive Director at the location
18 listed on the license, a license holder may store the products of other Maryland breweries
19 for the multibrewery activity.
20 (3) The multibrewery activity:
21 (i) may be held from 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. each day; and
22 (ii) may not exceed 3 consecutive days.
23 (j) The annual license fee:
24 (1) shall be determined by the Executive Director; and
25 (2) may not exceed $200.
26 (k) (1) On or before December 1 each year, the Executive Director shall report
27 to the Senate FINANCE Committee [on Education, Energy, and the Environment] and the
28 House [Economic Matters] GOVERNMENT, LABOR, AND ELECTIONS Committee, in
29 accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, the total beer production of each
30 Class 8 license holder in the preceding fiscal year, identified by jurisdiction and license
31 holder.

10 SENATE BILL 807
1 (2) Each holder of a Class 8 license shall report to the Executive Director
2 the information needed to prepare the annual report required under this subsection.
3 (3) The Executive Director shall include the information reported under
4 this subsection in the annual report submitted under § 1–316 of this article.
5 2–212.
6 (a) (1) This subsection does not apply to a Class 6 pub–brewery license.
7 (2) The holder of a distillery, FARM DISTILLERY, rectifying, winery,
8 limited winery, brewery, or farm brewery license may apply for and obtain, under a
9 different name, one or more additional distillery, FARM DISTILLERY, rectifying, winery,
10 limited winery, brewery, or farm brewery licenses for the same or different premises.
11 (3) (i) The holder of multiple manufacturer’s licenses at the same
12 location may allow the sampling, sales, and consumption of products produced under the
13 licenses at each of the licensed premises.
14 (ii) The sampling, sales, and consumption of products shall be
15 consistent with the authorization for each license.
16 (4) The additional licenses may be issued to different persons or under
17 trade names used by persons occupying all or a part of the same premises.
18 (5) A holder of a license listed in paragraph (2) of this subsection may hold
19 additional licenses listed in paragraph (2) of this subsection of the same or of a different
20 class.
21 (6) The holder of a micro–brewery license may apply for and obtain not
22 more than one additional micro–brewery license for another premises.
23 (b) (1) The holder of a rectifying or winery license may apply for and obtain a
24 wholesaler’s license of any class for the same premises or elsewhere as provided under this
25 article.
26 (2) The holder of a Class 4 limited winery license may apply for and obtain
27 a Class 6 limited wine wholesaler’s license for the same premises or elsewhere as provided
28 under this article.
29 (3) (i) The holder of a Class 5 brewery license or Class 7 micro–brewery
30 license may apply for and obtain a Class 7 limited beer wholesaler’s license in accordance
31 with this paragraph.
32 (ii) A holder of a Class 5 brewery license that was selling the holder’s
33 own beer at wholesale in the State as of January 1, 2013, may obtain a Class 7 limited beer

SENATE BILL 807 11
1 wholesaler’s license to continue to sell the holder’s own beer at wholesale in the same
2 location in an amount that is not more than 5,000 barrels annually.
3 (iii) A holder of a Class 5 brewery license that produces in aggregate
4 from all its locations not more than 45,000 barrels of beer annually may obtain a Class 7
5 limited beer wholesaler’s license and distribute not more than 5,000 barrels of its own beer
6 annually.
7 (4) A holder of one or two Class 7 micro–brewery licenses that produces in
8 aggregate from all of its locations not more than 45,000 barrels of beer annually may obtain
9 a Class 7 limited beer wholesaler’s license and distribute beer that:
10 (i) totals annually not more than 5,000 barrels in aggregate from all
11 of its locations; and
12 (ii) has been brewed at the location from where it is distributed.
13 (5) The holder of a Class 1 distillery license may apply for and obtain a
14 Class 8 liquor wholesaler’s license for the same premises or elsewhere as provided under
15 this article.
16 (6) The holder of a Class 9 limited distillery license OR A CLASS 10 FARM
17 DISTILLERY LICENSE may apply for and obtain a Class 8 liquor wholesaler’s license, for
18 the same premises or elsewhere as provided under this article, and distribute its own liquor.
19 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
20 1, 2026.
Approved:
